BATCH_PLAN_INSTRUCTION = 'You are creating a batch plan for generating synthetic inputs for a task.\n\nYou will receive:\n- The input data guide in <input_data_guide> tags\n- The task\'s input schema in <task_input_schema> tags (may be absent)\n- The task\'s output schema in <task_output_schema> tags (may be absent — describes\n  what the task PRODUCES from each input; context only, never generate outputs)\n- The task\'s instructions in <task_instruction> tags (this tells\n  you what the inputs are USED FOR; do NOT generate the task\'s output)\n- User guidance for this specific batch in <user_guidance> tags\n- Number of inputs to generate in <count> tags (N)\n\nA synthetic input is one example of the data that will be fed into the task at\nruntime. You turn high-level guidance into a set of N (<count>) specific prompts — one per\ninput — that a downstream generator each expands into a single realistic\nsynthetic input.\n\nHOW EACH PROMPT IS USED (read carefully):\nEach prompt you write is slotted in after a fixed instruction, roughly:\n  "Generate a synthetic input matching: <your prompt>"\nThe generator ALSO receives the full input data guide (and schema). Therefore:\n- Write each prompt as a DESCRIPTION of what makes THAT input distinct — not as a\n  standalone command. Do NOT begin with "Generate...", "Create...", "Write...",\n  or any imperative.\n- Include ONLY what VARIES across inputs. Do NOT restate attributes that are true\n  of EVERY input — the input type, universal formatting/wrapping, or any\n  constant the data guide already fixes for all inputs. The generator gets those\n  from the data guide; repeating them in every prompt is noise.\n- If a detail would be identical in all N prompts, it does not belong in any of\n  them.\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nFIRST: IDENTIFY INPUT TYPE\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nBefore anything else, determine if <user_guidance> specifies a DIFFERENT input type:\n1. INPUT TYPE REQUESTS in guidance:\n   - Explicit: "make them support tickets", "generate call transcripts instead of\n     emails", "write these as forum posts", etc.\n   - Naming a specific genre/format for the input indicates an input type change\n   - The input data guide\'s type is DEFAULT, a user-specified type OVERRIDES\n   - NOTE: a tone or style tweak ("make them more casual") is NOT a type change —\n     that\'s content/format guidance, handled lower in the cascade\n2. INPUT DATA GUIDE TYPE PRESERVATION:\n   - If no input type mentioned → use the data guide\'s type (default behavior)\n   - If an input type is specified → use that type entirely, the data guide\n     provides style/domain only\n3. SCHEMA PINS STRUCTURE:\n   - If <task_input_schema> is present, the input STRUCTURE is fixed by the schema\n     and CANNOT be overridden. An input-type override applies only to free-form\n     (schema-less) inputs. With a schema, user guidance still steers content,\n     style, and distribution — but never the shape.\nWrite your determination:\n"INPUT TYPE: [data guide type or user-specified type]"\n"SOURCE: [data guide semantics + user style] or [user semantics + data guide style]"\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nAUTHORITY CASCADE (use this to resolve ALL conflicts)\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nWhen instructions conflict, the HIGHER source wins — no exceptions:\n1. task_input_schema (when present) → defines the REQUIRED STRUCTURE: field names,\n   types, required vs optional, enums, formats. Never overridden.\n2. Input type from user → OVERRIDES the data guide\'s default type\n   (free-form inputs only; user says "call transcripts" → generate transcripts)\n3. User guidance for content/format → OVERRIDES data guide defaults\n   (For BOTH static template AND dynamic variable content)\n4. Input data guide → BASELINE when user doesn\'t specify\nINVARIANTS (never overridden):\n- Conformance to task_input_schema (fields, types, required, enums, formats)\n- Logical relationships between fields\n- Critical constraints and dependencies\n- Domain plausibility and accuracy\n"Maintain data guide patterns" = use the data guide WHERE USER HASN\'T SPECIFIED.\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nHOW THE DATA GUIDE AND SCHEMA RELATE\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nWhen <task_input_schema> is present, it is the authoritative source for field\nnames, top-level types, required vs optional, cardinality, enums, and any value\nformats it states explicitly. The input data guide deliberately does NOT restate\nanything the schema already captures. Treat them as complementary:\n- Schema = the exact structure and field-level constraints every input must satisfy.\n- Data guide = everything the schema can\'t express — realistic content,\n  distributions, relationships, plausibility.\nTogether they define a valid input. Only plan inputs the schema can represent.\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nUSING THE TASK OUTPUT SCHEMA (context only)\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nWhen <task_output_schema> is present, its fields and especially their DESCRIPTIONS\noften carry domain context the task instruction omits — what the task\ndiscriminates, the categories/ranges it produces, and the edge cases that matter.\nUse it for two things:\n- REALISM: plan inputs that could plausibly produce a valid output under this schema.\n- COVERAGE: spread the batch so it exercises the meaningful range of outputs — e.g.\n  inputs that would land on different enum values, boundary cases, and the\n  situations the output descriptions call out — instead of clustering on one.\nHard limits:\n- NEVER generate the task\'s output, label, or answer. You plan INPUTS only.\n- Do NOT engineer inputs to be artificially easy or to telegraph a specific output.\n  Realistic inputs — including ambiguous or hard ones — are the goal, not\n  label-leaking ones.\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nYour task:\n1. Create a "summary" field: a short, polished overview of the batch for the user\n2. Create a "prompts" array with SPECIFIC, CONCRETE guidance for EACH individual input\nCRITICAL: Each prompt must be a SPECIFIC INSTANTIATION of user guidance, not a repetition.\nSUMMARY: A short, polished overview of the batch, written FOR THE USER — it\nwill be shown directly in the UI, so it must read like a clean, finished summary,\nnot internal notes or scratch work.\n- Open with one plain-language sentence: what\'s being generated and how many.\n- Then a scannable bulleted breakdown of the composition — distribution across the\n  dimensions that vary (percentages or counts), plus any notable emphases, edge\n  cases, or deliberate departures from the usual inputs, in plain terms.\n- Use percentages/counts so the user grasps the mix at a glance without reading\n  the individual prompts.\n- Audience-appropriate: NO internal jargon ("data guide", "corpus", "off book",\n  "schema", "authority cascade") and NO meta-commentary about your process —\n  just describe the batch the user is about to generate.\nExample summary:\n  Generating 50 vendor contracts for small businesses:\n  - 50% beer/wine suppliers, 25% caterers, 25% woodworking shops\n  - All in Canadian legal style, Ontario jurisdiction\n  - A handful include extended termination clauses for higher-value deals\nWhen instantiating guidance:\n1. ALWAYS respect CRITICAL SEMANTIC CONSTRAINTS from the data guide and schema:\n   - Schema conformance must be maintained (fields, types, required, enums, formats)\n   - Field dependencies must be maintained\n   - Logical consistency must be preserved\n   - Context-appropriate values must be used\n2. Handle generation mode based on user guidance:\n   - FAITHFUL generation: Pick values matching typical data guide patterns\n   - DIVERGENT generation: When user requests edge cases or unusual combinations, respect divergence while maintaining logical consistency\n3. PRESENTATION/FORMAT HANDLING:\n   User guidance can specify format EXPLICITLY or IMPLICITLY:\n   EXPLICIT: Direct statements about format, structure, or regional conventions\n   IMPLICIT: Values/units/formats used in guidance ARE format signal.\n   When user guidance uses specific units, date formats, terminology, or\n   conventions, those choices define the output format. Do NOT convert them\n   back to data guide defaults.\n   CRITICAL RULES:\n   A. PRESERVE format signals: If user guidance uses specific formats, units, or\n      conventions, your prompts MUST continue using those. Do NOT convert back to\n      data guide defaults.\n   B. COMPLETE STANDARD: A regional/style request means ALL conventions from that\n      standard, not just explicitly mentioned fields.\n   C. STRUCTURAL FORMATS ARE VALID: Requests about section ordering, omissions,\n      or input organization are presentation requirements. Include them in\n      prompt guidance.\n4. INPUT TYPE SPECIFIC GUIDANCE:\nWhen user requests a DIFFERENT input type (free-form inputs only; e.g., "make\nthese call transcripts"):\n- Structure prompts to reflect the REQUESTED input type\'s structure\n- The data guide contributes: writing style, domain knowledge, quality standards\n- Example: If the data guide describes support emails and guidance says "call\n  transcripts", prompts should describe spoken back-and-forth, not email content\n- BAD prompt: "Subject line, greeting, body paragraph about a billing dispute..."\n  (this keeps the data guide\'s email structure)\n- GOOD prompt: "Transcript of a 4-minute call: customer disputes a $42 billing\n  charge, agent looks up the account, identifies a duplicate charge, issues a\n  refund, customer thanks them..."\n  (this uses transcript structure with the data guide\'s domain knowledge)\nEach prompt should:\n- Be distinct from other prompts (no copy-paste repetition)\n- Include ONLY the per-input variation — never restate constants shared by all\n  inputs (input type, universal formatting/wrapping, anything the data guide\n  fixes for every input). Those come from the data guide the generator also sees.\n- Be phrased as a description of the distinct input, NOT an imperative command\n  (no leading "Generate...", "Create...", "Write...")\n- Include specific values, not ranges or placeholders\n- When a prompt diverges from the usual inputs in any MEASURABLE way (length,\n  verbosity, section counts, value ranges), state EXPLICIT numeric bounds, not\n  vague qualifiers. BAD: "much longer and more detailed." GOOD: "expand to\n  100-150 words, 5-7 sentences (usual: ~40 words)."\n- Conform to task_input_schema when present (valid fields, types, enums, formats)\n- Add realistic secondary details from the data guide\n- Tell a slightly different story while satisfying user guidance\n- RESPECT all critical semantic constraints\n- PRESERVE all format/presentation requirements from user guidance\n- VARY AUXILIARY/CONDITIONAL DATA: Spread variable elements across the batch —\n  don\'t default to the most common pattern for every prompt. Draw these axes from\n  BOTH sources: the schema (optional fields — include in some, omit in others; and\n  enums — spread the allowed values across the batch), and the data guide (any\n  sections or data subtypes it marks as conditional or variable). Diversify what\n  types of auxiliary data appear, not just the primary content.\nBAD prompts (imperative framing, restating a constant true of every input, and\njust echoing the guidance — note "<shared input type/format>" is fixed by the data\nguide for ALL inputs, so it\'s noise, and the two prompts are interchangeable):\n- Prompt 1: "Generate one <shared input type/format> with characteristic A in range X-Y"\n- Prompt 2: "Generate one <shared input type/format> with characteristic A in range X-Y"\nGOOD prompts (no command, no shared constants — only the concrete per-input\nvariation, with format signals preserved and conditional data varied):\n- Prompt 1: "Entity P: A = X (in the requested units), constraint Y satisfied, plus\n  distinguishing context C"\n- Prompt 2: "Entity Q: A = X\' (a different value), optional section D included this\n  time, constraint Y still satisfied, different context E"\n\nReturn ONLY a JSON object:\n{\n  "prompts": ["guidance for input 1", "guidance for input 2", ..., "guidance for input N"]\n  "summary": "Short, polished, user-facing overview of the batch...",\n}'

BATCH_PLAN_OUTPUT_SCHEMA = '{"type":"object","properties":{"prompts":{"type":"array","description":"One entry per input to generate; the array length must equal the requested count. Each entry drives the generation of a single synthetic input.","items":{"type":"string","description":"A single generation prompt describing ONLY what makes this one input distinct from the others (the per-input variation). Written as a description of the input, not an imperative command - no leading \'Generate\', \'Create\', or \'Write\'. Must not restate attributes shared by every input (the input type, universal formatting/wrapping, or anything the data guide fixes for all inputs), since the downstream generator also receives the data guide. Uses specific concrete values rather than ranges or placeholders, conforms to the task input schema when one is present, preserves any format signals from the user guidance, and states explicit numeric bounds for any measurable divergence from the usual inputs."}},"summary":{"type":"string","description":"A short, polished, user-facing overview of the batch, shown directly in the UI. Start with one plain-language sentence stating what is being generated and how many. Follow with a scannable bulleted breakdown of the composition: distribution across the dimensions that vary (percentages or counts), plus any notable emphases, edge cases, or deliberate departures from the usual inputs. Must read like a finished summary, not scratch work. Do not use internal jargon (e.g. \'data guide\', \'corpus\', \'schema\', \'off book\', \'authority cascade\') and do not include meta-commentary about the planning process."}},"required":["prompts","summary"],"additionalProperties":false}'
